           Diskmag News - All the stuff vaguely fit to print  

Lots  (at least two things) going on this time around as DBA  close  and 
FOG is reborn!

The   well-known  Dutch  Falcon  scene  publication,   the   Diskbusters 
Association Magazine (DBA Mag) is no more! (Scream!)

The reasons why they have discontinued are still unclear at this  stage, 
but it seems that Slimer may well have experienced differences with some 
of the co-writers,  although this is unconfirmed.. Also very possible is 
a general disenchantment with the 'scene' and scene related  activites.. 
From  talking to him at Symposium,  it was clear then,  that DBA did not 
have many more issues in them and Slimer himself was contemplating going 
more  to the 'business' side of things..  Indeed ample evidence of  this 
disenchantment can be found in the Symposium 'Realtime' article text now 
viewing in this issue of Maggie instead.. 

As  with Richard Karsmakers,  there may well be future appearances in  a 
future issue of Maggie with the odd textfile (or three!) by him.. 

On  the good news front,  it seems that John Nott (aka VoGue) has  taken 
over Richard Davey's interest in the Falcon Owners Group (FOG), and also 
the  largely  defunct 'Falcon Update Digital' diskmag with  it..  Rumour 
control in the latter part of 1995 was unable to entirely suppress  talk 
of  a new and superbly programmed custom Falcon shell written by  Al  of 
Psychosis for FOG, but never used by Rich Davey.. Now Rich's Falcon, and 
FOG  have  all fallen into the hands of VoGue,  the man  behind  'Skynet 
Times', who gave up that magazine largely through lack of a decent shell 
program..

Now  he  may have the last laugh on all of us!  Hope to see it  sometime 
before Maggie 22, and great to have a new competing diskmag..

More as we get it..

Also  this time,  word of another HTML based publication,  'Atari Times' 
which  started out life as the Croft Soft newsletter has  reached  issue 
four  as  of August 1996..  As well as specific information about  Croft 
Soft,  and  the  games they are releasing,  there is also a mixed bag of 
reviews,  previews  and more general news too..  Presentation is sparse, 
compared with some other recent HTML-based efforts, but good enough, and 
reasonably  informative..  One which seems to get bigger with each issue 
and  worth  keeping  an  eye  on..  More of their  newest  game  in  the 
'Previews' column as well..

Another  'newbie'  diskmag,  ST  Highway has reached issue  three..  Not 
seeing  a  lot  of it before,  first impressions are a  bit  vague,  but 
stylistically  seems  to be a 'younger' version of Kelstar..  It uses  a 
very similar interpretation of the TOMS shell.. Some articles promising, 
others  netgrabs or bobbins,  the usual mix for a young diskmag in other 
words.. We'll see how they develop as time goes on in future issues.. 


                     **Late News update on DBA!!**

At  this  late stage (nine days to release date) we have  received  word 
from  Bonus and some of the other members of DBA..  It seems that DBA is 
dead,  but the Dutch scene live on with a new group being established to 
work  on various games and demos,  and even a CD-ROM compilation for the 
Falcon..  Amongst other things,  an 'unofficial' release of DBA issue 15 
is  on the cards as well..  The DBA Symposium realtime article and other 
DBA  material  scheduled  to appear here has  been  'pulled'  from  this 
issue..  Which is not necessarily a bad thing as space is getting rather 
tight  in here!!  (Although if nothing happens by the time Maggie 22  is 
ready, we may well reinstate that material!!)

More  specific  information can be found in the 'letters' column  as  to 
what Bonus is doing in the near future..

That's your lot for diskzines this time folks!

